# Sartorius

> The **sartorius** is the longest muscle in the human body (~50 cm), running diagonally across the anterior thigh from the [[Anterior Superior Iliac Spine|ASIS]] to the medial tibia (pes anserinus). It flexes, abducts, and externally rotates the hip, and flexes the knee.

## 🔗 Key Connections
- **Origin** — [[Anterior Superior Iliac Spine|ASIS]] of [[Hip Bone]]
- **Insertion** — Pes anserinus (medial [[Tibia]]) — with gracilis + semitendinosus
- **Nerve** — [[Femoral Nerve]] (L2, L3)
- **Action** — Hip flexion + abduction + ER; knee flexion ("tailor's position")

## 🏥 Clinical Significance
- **Pes anserinus bursitis** — Inflammation at the pes anserinus insertion; medial knee pain
- **ASIS avulsion** — Sartorius avulsion fracture in adolescents during sprinting

